Thanks, Art... all that you bring with you will add to this circle.<br><br>
We all think in icons, images and symbols.  When I ponder the Medicine Wheel, I remember that it begins in the East.  That is also where each day begins.  The color for the East is yellow or gold, symbolic of daylight.  Indeed, the word from the East is &quot;illumination.&quot;  The animal brother who sits there is Wambli, the eagle, a symbol of clear far reaching vision.  The East is symbolic of beginnings.  Each rite of passage is essentially a new beginning.<br>
At the beginning of anything there is a need for illumination and a holistic view.  A project is started an idea conceived.<br>
In the South, the color is green, suggesting new growth.  The Spring and Summer come from the South following the beginning of a new year.  After one conceives an idea that idea must grow. The Mouse, small ear, sits in the South to remind us that it is wise to remember two words: &quot;innocence and trust.&quot;<br>
Without innocence and trust it is difficult to grow in learning.  Many new ventures fail because one does not learn as he goes.  The close scruitny of the Mouse suggests close up seeing and attention to detail as a beginning unfolds.<br>
The West is where the day ends.  Many other things in life have endings.  Projects are completed, a painting is finished, a song is sung, and a baseball game is over.  In the West the color is black.  Black portends the end of something.  The Bear, Matho, sits in the West.  His eyesight is poor outwardly, but suggests the word and merits of &quot;Introspection.&quot;  We look inward after the project is finished, our contributions made, our lives lived and contemplate, &quot;How did I do?&quot; <br>
From there we journey to the North, which is White.  The word is &quot;Wisdom.&quot;  The Brother who sits there is Tatanka Ska, the white buffalo.  A beginning has occured, growth has happened, an inward evaluation and assesment of knowledge completed and ultimately Wisdom is born.  Wise, as in direction (Clock wise) dom as in domain (the home or place of) Wise+dom = wisdom.<br>
Before becoming Dog Soldiers, Akicita Was'te we were young men sitting in the East with a global picture but no close scruitny.  There was light but we did not know what we were seeing.  We followed the words of Tunkasila, and Ate', our Grandfathers, Fathers and Uncles.  We came to the place of the South and we grew stronger as novice warriors.  Some came and did not find innocence and trust but sought arrogance and suspicion.  They would learn the hard way, Kaonspe, teaching and learning with force.<br>
Between the South and West we would know war, and upon reaching the West some would know that blackness called death.  Others would look at the blackness inside and decide &quot;Did I do the right things, expected of a man?  Do I know the way of Hecitu yelo, the way of the truth?&quot; Knowledge would come from war, but like many colored leaves it would scatter before the winds of confusion.<br>
After the journey to the North, young wounded Dog Soldiers will sit by the warriors with the White hair and their knowledge shall become wisdom.
